- [ ] Saves session mappings correctly with projectPath
- [ ] Removes session mappings correctly
- [ ] Atomic file writes (no partial writes)
- [ ] Updates lastAccessedAt on touch

## Task

Create `GET /api/health/opencode` - An endpoint to check if the OpenCode server is reachable.

## Why

The frontend needs to know if OpenCode is available before attempting to use it. This enables:
- Showing helpful error messages ("Start opencode serve")
- Disabling chat UI when OpenCode is down
- Periodic connectivity checks

## Implementation

Use the SDK's built-in `client.global.health()` method:

```typescript
// src/app/api/health/opencode/route.ts

import { openCodeService } from "@/lib/services/opencode"
import { NextResponse } from "next/server"

export async function GET() {
  try {
    const healthy = await openCodeService.isHealthy()

    if (healthy) {
      return NextResponse.json({
        status: "healthy",
        url: process.env.OPENCODE_URL || "http://localhost:4096"
      })
    } else {
      return NextResponse.json({
        status: "unhealthy",
        error: "OpenCode server not responding"
      }, { status: 503 })
    }
  } catch (error) {
    return NextResponse.json({
      status: "unhealthy",
      error: error instanceof Error ? error.message : "Unknown error"
    }, { status: 503 })
  }
}
```

## SDK Health Check

The SDK provides `client.global.health()` which returns:
```typescript
{ healthy: true, version: string }
```

This is the recommended way to check connectivity.

## Response Format

```typescript
// Success (200)
{
  status: "healthy",
  url: "http://localhost:4096"
}

// Failure (503)
{
  status: "unhealthy",
  error: "Connection refused" // or similar
}
```

## Usage in Frontend

```typescript
// Poll health periodically
const { data: health } = useQuery({
  queryKey: ["opencode-health"],
  queryFn: () => fetch("/api/health/opencode").then(r => r.json()),
  refetchInterval: 30000, // Every 30 seconds
})

if (health?.status !== "healthy") {
  // Show error banner
}
```

