## Purpose
Create the breadcrumb navigation component for the folder browser. Shows the current path as clickable segments, allowing users to jump to any parent directory.

## Visual Design
```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  ~ / dev / projects / my-app        [↑] │
└─────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

- Each segment is clickable
- Current directory (last segment) is not clickable, just highlighted
- "Up" button navigates to parent (same as clicking second-to-last segment)
- On mobile, breadcrumbs scroll horizontally

## Props
```typescript
interface BreadcrumbsProps {
  displayPath: string;       // e.g., "~/dev/projects/my-app"
  onNavigate: (path: string) => void;
  parent: string | null;     // Absolute path of parent, null if at home
  canGoUp: boolean;
}
```

## Implementation
```typescript
// src/components/folder-browser/Breadcrumbs.tsx
import { ChevronUp, Home } from "lucide-react";
import { cn } from "@/lib/utils";

export function Breadcrumbs({ displayPath, onNavigate, parent, canGoUp }: BreadcrumbsProps) {
  // Parse displayPath into segments
  // "~/dev/projects" → ["~", "dev", "projects"]
  const segments = displayPath.split("/").filter(Boolean);

  // Build absolute paths for each segment
  // We need to map display paths back to absolute paths for navigation
  // This requires knowing the home directory or receiving absolute paths
  // For simplicity, receive absolutePath as well or compute from displayPath

  return (
    <div className="flex items-center gap-1 px-3 py-2 border-b border-border overflow-x-auto">
      {/* Scrollable breadcrumb container */}
      <div className="flex items-center gap-1 min-w-0 flex-1">
        {segments.map((segment, index) => {
          const isLast = index === segments.length - 1;
          const isHome = segment === "~";

          // Compute path for this segment
          // "~/dev/projects" at index 1 ("dev") → "~/dev" → need absolute
          // This is tricky - see implementation note below

          return (
            <div key={index} className="flex items-center">
              {index > 0 && (
                <span className="text-muted-foreground mx-1">/</span>
              )}
              {isLast ? (
                <span className="font-medium truncate">{segment}</span>
              ) : (
                <button
                  onClick={() => onNavigate(pathForSegment)}
                  className="text-muted-foreground hover:text-foreground transition-colors truncate"
                >
                  {isHome ? <Home className="h-3.5 w-3.5" /> : segment}
                </button>
              )}
            </div>
          );
        })}
      </div>

      {/* Up button */}
      <button
        onClick={() => parent && onNavigate(parent)}
        disabled={!canGoUp}
        className={cn(
          "h-8 w-8 flex items-center justify-center rounded-md transition-colors",
          canGoUp 
            ? "hover:bg-secondary text-muted-foreground hover:text-foreground" 
            : "text-muted-foreground/30 cursor-not-allowed"
        )}
        aria-label="Go to parent directory"
      >
        <ChevronUp className="h-4 w-4" />
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Path Mapping Challenge
The displayPath is `~/dev/projects` but we need absolute paths for navigation. Solutions:

1. **Pass absolutePath as prop** (recommended)
   - FolderBrowser has both from useFilesystem response
   - Breadcrumbs receives both and uses absolute for onClick

2. **Reconstruct from segments**
   - Replace `~` with home directory
   - Join segments with `/`
   - More brittle, assumes path format

Going with option 1:
```typescript
interface BreadcrumbsProps {
  currentPath: string;       // Absolute: /Users/erik/dev/projects
  displayPath: string;       // Display: ~/dev/projects
  onNavigate: (path: string) => void;
  parent: string | null;
  canGoUp: boolean;
}
```

Then compute segment paths by walking back from currentPath.

